DB','','publish','open','closed','','dynamo-db-2','','','2020-05-27 19:24:28','2020-05-27 19:24:28','',0,'http://127.0.0.1/wordpress/wp1/?post_type=shop_question&#038;p=710',0,'shop_question','',0),(711,1,'2020-05-27 19:41:50','2020-05-27 19:41:50','Let\'s talk about DynamoDB.\r\nSo this is Werner Vogels.\r\nHe\'s pretty much a badass.\r\nHe\'s a passionate technologist\r\nand he loves electronic dance music,\r\nand oh yeah, he just happens to be the CTO of Amazon.\r\nWell back in 2007, Werner and his colleagues\r\nwrote a paper describing Dynamo.\r\nIt\'s this massively scalable key value storage system,\r\nwhich was a blueprint of what we now call DynamoDB.\r\nNow as you might already know, DynamoDB is a managed\r\nmulti-AZ, NoSQL data store.\r\nAnd it has available cross-region replication,\r\nso that means we can replicate our data\r\naround the globe if we want, and keep it safe.\r\nNow since DynamoDB is a multi-AZ implementation,\r\nit takes a little while for the rights to be propagated\r\nacross all AZ\'s,\r\nhence the term eventual consistency.\r\nNow this usually takes less than a second,\r\nand what this means is if you make a write,\r\nthen you immediately make a read really soon afterwards.\r\nIt\'s possible that your read might reflect the old data.\r\nNow if it\'s really, really important that you always\r\nget the latest and greatest,\r\nthen you can request a strongly consistent read,\r\nwhich will return the absolute latest update\r\nregardless of whether it\'s been propagated across AZ\'s.\r\nNow you might think you want to always do this\r\nbut the downside is that\r\nif there\'s a network delay or an outage of the AZ\r\nthat happens to have your latest update,\r\nyour read might fail.\r\nNow there\'s something else at play here too.\r\nNormally we talk about DynamoDB\r\nas being more on a base compliant of the consistency model\r\nas opposed to ACID, but DynamoDB also has the ability\r\nto conduct ACID compliant transactions.\r\nAnd we\'ll talk about this in a bit.\r\nNow generally, DynamoDB is priced on throughput\r\nrather than compute.\r\nSo, you can define how many read and write capacity units\r\nthat you\'re gonna need.\r\nNow you can also use auto scaling\r\nbut it\'s not necessarily all that it\'s cracked up to be.\r\nHow auto scaling works is it watches the table\r\nfor a consistent, elevated stream of requests\r\neither read or write,\r\nand then that can then trigger a CloudWatch alarm,\r\nwhich then in turn triggers a scale-up\r\nfor the read and write capacity of the table.\r\nNow on the flip side, once you don\'t need that capacity\r\nanymore, if you have no transactions going to the table,\r\nthen it\'s not gonna scale back down\r\nbecause DynamoDB doesn\'t know if it\'s just a lull\r\nin the traffic, and it\'s getting ready\r\nto get hammered again.\r\nOr if it truly doesn\'t need that capacity again.\r\nSo there are some workarounds the documentation suggests\r\nlike sending in synthetic transactions\r\nto kind of taper off the load,\r\nand bring them the read and write capacity units\r\nback down to their minimum.\r\nBut those may or may not work as you would expect them.\r\nNow the alternative is if you have no idea\r\nhow many read and write capacity units\r\nyou\'re gonna need, you can use something\r\ncalled on-demand capacity.\r\nAnd that just scales to whatever size you need it to be.\r\nAnd there is a small premium cost for that.\r\nIt\'s definitely more cost effective\r\nif you provision the read and write capacity in advance\r\nversus using on-demand capacity,\r\nbut in some use cases, you just don\'t know what\r\nyour read and write capacity is gonna be.\r\nand you don\'t want to mess with auto scaling.\r\nSo on demand capacity might be for you.\r\nNow there\'s also the option to achieve ACID compliance\r\nwith something called DynamoDB transactions.\r\nNow the SDK has a method with which we can put\r\nand get records and the table will implement ACID compliance\r\nfor us for those records.\r\nNow that\'s really interesting,\r\nbecause now it opens DynamoDB up to a bunch of new use cases\r\nor traditionally maybe we were restricted\r\nto an RDBMS system because we needed\r\nthat ACID compliance.\r\nNow let\'s talk a little bit about the comparison\r\nbetween relational databases and NoSQL databases.\r\nRelational databases are best when the data\r\nis structured very well, relational.\r\nSomewhere along the road you might have been exposed\r\nto entity relationship diagrams like this\r\nwith the crow\'s feet and the symbols and such.\r\nAnd this concept\'s been around for a really long time\r\nand relational databases support this well\r\nin the form of tables and fields.\r\nNow NoSQL databases are designed to excel\r\nat managing name value pairs.\r\nSo, a NoSQL record is usually self-contained\r\nand doesn\'t have to relate\r\nto any other tables to make sense.\r\nHere in this example we have a simple JSON string\r\nthat has name and values.\r\nAnd together the name value pairs are known\r\nas an attribute.\r\nWe have the item, which is the whole collection\r\nof name and values.\r\nMany of these records come together to form a table.\r\nAs you might expect, every record has to have\r\nsomething that uniquely identifies it.\r\nAnd in DynamoDB, we call this the primary key.\r\nNow it must be unique.\r\nSo, in this case we\'ve chosen sales order number\r\nas our unique primary key.\r\nNow DynamoDB is gonna use this key value\r\nto create an internal hash.\r\nThat\'s just a way to map a data value of arbitrary size\r\nto one of fixed size.\r\nIt uses this hash to decide which partition\r\nor underlying physical storage\r\nto store the value.\r\nSometimes this is called a hash attribute.\r\nThere\'s another way you can key a table.\r\nSo in this case, we\'ve chosen\r\nboth salesOrderNum and timestamp.\r\nA salesOrderNum is known as the partition key,\r\nand the timestamp is known as the sort key.\r\nNow we can have occurrences of the same partition key\r\nas long as the sort key is different.\r\nThe same hash is done to the partition key\r\nbut in addition, the records are stored in the sort\r\norder of the sort key.\r\nThis is useful if you want to pull back a subset of data\r\nbased on some sort key.\r\nIn this case let\'s say our application\r\nnever edit a sales order,\r\nit just created new versions of it.\r\nSo, if we queried only the sales order number,\r\nwe might get back a bunch of records.\r\nIf we also passed in something that said\r\nreturn the max timestamp,\r\nthen we\'d only get back one record,\r\nand it\'d be really, really fast.\r\nWe also have secondary indexes.\r\nThe first one\'s called a global secondary index\r\nand the partition key and the sort key\r\ncan be different from those on the table.\r\nThe second type of index is called local secondary index.\r\nNow it has to have the same partition key,\r\nbut it can have a different sort key.\r\nNow how can you remember these?\r\nWell for a global secondary index,\r\nI\'m not restricted by the partition key.\r\nI can go anywhere.\r\nI\'m global baby.\r\nFor the local secondary, I have to stay local\r\nand respect the table\'s partition key,\r\nbut I can choose whatever sort key I want.\r\nNow there\'s some limitations here\r\nand also these indexes take up storage space.\r\nLet\'s take a closer look at the secondary indexes\r\nand where we would actually use them.\r\nIf you want a fast query of attributes\r\noutside the primary key without having\r\nto do a full table scan,\r\nmeaning reading everything sequentially.\r\nThat\'s where a global secondary index really\r\ncomes into handy.\r\nFor example in our sales order,\r\nI\'d like to query the sales orders by customer number\r\nrather than sales order number.\r\nIf you already know the partition key,\r\nbut you just want to quickly query\r\non some other attribute,\r\nthat\'s where local secondary index comes into play.\r\nAn example we have here is if we already\r\nhave our sales order number,\r\nbut I want to retrieve only those records\r\nwith a certain material number.\r\nSo, here\'s what it might look like on our sample record.\r\nSuppose we created a global secondary on customer number,\r\nwe could query by customer number at lightning speed.\r\nNow suppose we created a local secondary\r\nusing material number.\r\nSo we could query by a sales order number\r\nand material number at lightning speed.\r\nWhen you create an index, you need to select which\r\nattributes that will be projected on to that index.\r\nIf you\'re familiar with traditional relational database\r\nconcepts, a secondary index is kind of like a view.\r\nYou select a subset of attributes to be part of that\r\nsecondary index but no more than 20 across all indexes.\r\nIn this case, we\'ve created a global secondary index\r\nwith customer number as the key.\r\nAnd then we\'ve added customer name, customer address,\r\nsales order number and the timestamp.\r\nSo here are a few use cases to determine\r\nwhether a secondary index is gonna benefit you.\r\nIf you just need to access a few attributes\r\nin the fastest way possible,\r\nyou can project those few attributes\r\nin a global secondary index.\r\nAnd the cost is minimal and that\'s gonna give you\r\nthe lowest possible latency for accessing non-key items.\r\nNow if you need to frequently access non-key items,\r\nyou can still project those attributes\r\nin a global secondary index.\r\nBut it\'s gonna be a little bit more costly.\r\nBut the aim there is to offset the cost of table scans.\r\nNow if you need to frequently access most non-key attributes\r\nprojecting those attributes or even the entire table\r\non a global secondary, is an option,\r\nbut the cost could be up to double\r\nbecause in essence you\'re duplicating the table.\r\nBut you have maximum flexibility.\r\nNow let\'s say you rarely query\r\nbut you write an update frequently.\r\nProjecting those keys that you use for the write updates\r\nis pretty effective.\r\nThe cost is minimal but it gives you really fast writes\r\nand updates for the non partition key items.\r\nI wanted to go into a little bit more detail\r\naround DynamoDB design practices,\r\nbecause this is something that tends to appear on the exam\r\nand plus it\'s pretty cool.\r\nLet\'s take for example this set of data.\r\nThere\'s three different records here.\r\nThey all share this common partition key\r\nbut they have different values for the sort key.\r\nThe sort key is still the same name for the attribute\r\nin all three records but we\'ve assigned different values\r\nto that sort key.\r\nIn fact we can look at these records like this as well.\r\nNow if you\'re a die-hard relational database person\r\nlike I am, this design may look really strange to you\r\nand probably violates what you were taught\r\nabout normalization.\r\nHowever, just stick with me for a bit.\r\nWe\'re in a NoSQL world here,\r\nso that lets us use some tricks\r\nthat can provide greater flexibility\r\nand can improve performance for us.\r\nSo, we have our partition keys\r\nand we have our sort keys.\r\nSo, we can pull up any record really fast\r\nwith these two.\r\nThere\'s nothing new here,\r\nbut let\'s say we wanted a way to quickly update\r\nor pull total purchases across all customers.\r\nWe could define a global secondary index\r\nwith period as the primary key and total purchases\r\nas an attribute.\r\nNow we can very quickly perform aggregations based on date,\r\nmaybe in this case we want to query the table\r\nto find out the total purchases across all customers\r\nfor the period of March 2019.\r\nAnother strategy we can use is to leverage sparse indexes.\r\nIf we continue along with our example\r\nof a global secondary index on period,\r\nyou\'ll notice that not every record\r\nhas an attribute called period.\r\nA neat trick of DynamoDB\r\nis that the index will only exist for those items\r\nthat have the period attribute,\r\nwhich means the index is smaller\r\nand will incur fewer reads and writes.\r\nWe can also use a global secondary index\r\nto create table replicas.\r\nWe just have to use the same partition key and sort key\r\nas the original table\r\nand one or more attributes.\r\nWhen might we do this?\r\nLet\'s say for example we have two tiers of customers.\r\nWe have premium customers\r\nand maybe free tier customers.\r\nFor our premium customers we want to be sure\r\nthat they\'re not going to run into any performance issues.\r\nSo, we will permit them to do their reads and writes\r\nagainst a DynamoDB table, that has a higher\r\nRCU and WCU limit.\r\nNow we still want to serve up that same data\r\nto our free tier customers\r\nbut maybe we provision a global secondary index\r\nand put a lower RCU WCU limit\r\non that particular index.\r\nAnother use case might be for performance reasons.\r\nLet\'s say we want to have high write capacities\r\non our original table.\r\nAnd that\'s the table we use\r\nto stream in data very quickly.\r\nAnd then maybe we want a replica of that table,\r\nso that we can perform our read analysis\r\nand will have a very high read capacity limit on that table.\r\nSo, that we\'re not trying to do analysis on the same table\r\nwe\'re continually writing into.\r\nNow something to keep in mind\r\nis that the replica is eventually consistent,\r\nmeaning that there might very well be a very small delay\r\nbetween when the original table gets updated,\r\nand the replica gets updated.\r\nIn most cases though, this is probably less\r\nthan a second or two\r\nand it probably isn\'t going to cause big issues,\r\nbut it\'s something to be aware of.','','','publish','open','open','','711','','','2020-05-27 19:41:50','2020-05-27 19:41:50','',0,'http://127.0.0.1/wordpress/wp1/?p=711',0,'post','',0),(712,1,'2020-05-27 19:24:41','2020-05-27 19:24:41','Let\'s talk about DynamoDB.\r\nSo this is Werner Vogels.\r\nHe\'s pretty much a badass.\r\nHe\'s a passionate technologist\r\nand he loves electronic dance 